                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d115">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.93 Outer Mongolia/16: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Second Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-04-30T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >April 30, 1936—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 30—10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>114. My 90, April 12, 9 [<hi rend="italic">11</hi>] a.m.<note n="61a"
                        xml:id="d115fn61a">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>I am informed by a responsible official of the Foreign Office that no
                        reply from the Soviet Government has been received to the Chinese second
                        protest of April 11. He stated that unless the Soviet Government replied,
                        the Chinese Government would send the former no further communication on the
                        subject and would assume that the Soviet Government accepted China’s
                        position as set forth in the Chinese notes of April 7 and 11. He did not
                        believe that the Soviet Union would cancel the pact of March 12 with Outer
                        Mongolia but considered that <pb facs="0223" n="128" xml:id="pg_128"/>
                        failure to do so “would not matter because to the Chinese Government the
                        pact is non-existent.”</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Repeated to the Department and Peiping. By mail to Moscow.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
